WEBVTT

00:04.033 --> 00:06.135
Well, there's a sight
that never gets old.

00:06.136 --> 00:09.505
You know, if men knew how sexy
they looked fixing stuff,

00:09.506 --> 00:10.807
they'd never stop.

00:10.808 --> 00:12.442
I can't feel my hands.

00:12.443 --> 00:13.810
Well, why don't you
bring them down here

00:13.811 --> 00:16.111
and let me do something about it?

00:16.846 --> 00:18.715
Where are the kids?

00:18.716 --> 00:22.352
They're out riding... till dark.

00:22.353 --> 00:25.488
I should really finish up here.

00:25.489 --> 00:27.490
Okay.

00:27.491 --> 00:28.958
I'll go riding, too.

00:28.959 --> 00:31.361
Coming down.

00:31.362 --> 00:33.596
Oh, man, it's so silent here.

00:33.597 --> 00:36.466
I'd forgotten what that sounded like.

00:36.467 --> 00:38.801
Are you thinking what I'm thinking?

00:38.802 --> 00:40.136
We shouldn't sell.

00:40.137 --> 00:42.505
- We so shouldn't sell!
- But wait,

00:42.506 --> 00:44.374
you're the one that tried to
convince me that we should.

00:44.375 --> 00:46.676
Well, it's hard keeping up two homes.

00:46.677 --> 00:48.378
And we hardly even ever get back here.

00:48.379 --> 00:51.214
Yeah, upkeep on the property,
the horses, the repairs.

00:51.215 --> 00:52.849
I know. I was present
for that conversation.

00:52.850 --> 00:53.883
Present and persuaded...

00:53.884 --> 00:56.018
On the other hand, this is home.

00:56.019 --> 00:57.687
I mean, this is where we're gonna come

00:57.688 --> 00:59.288
back to after my job, right?

00:59.289 --> 01:00.923
This is our normal.

01:00.924 --> 01:02.492
Yeah, but what happened
to never looking back?

01:02.493 --> 01:03.659
I'm looking forward.

01:03.660 --> 01:06.295
- To getting back to our old selves.
- Yeah, but...

01:06.296 --> 01:09.465
You know, your job could go on
for several more years, babe.

01:09.466 --> 01:11.868
- So...
- All the more reason to have a touchstone.

01:11.869 --> 01:13.202
We shouldn't sell.

01:13.203 --> 01:14.871
On the other hand,

01:14.872 --> 01:17.540
did you see the electric
bill from the horse barn?

01:17.541 --> 01:19.909
- Okay.
- And the property taxes are insane.

01:19.910 --> 01:21.344
You see how you just...

01:21.345 --> 01:23.079
I'm verbally processing. I'm...

01:23.080 --> 01:24.347
Hey.

01:24.348 --> 01:25.515
What are you guys doing back?

01:25.516 --> 01:28.217
Hey, we saw a rabbit chasing a fox!

01:28.218 --> 01:30.620
- Uh, don't you mean...?
- JASON: Nope.

01:30.621 --> 01:32.388
Huge rabbit, skinny fox.

01:32.389 --> 01:34.791
- There's a parable there.
- (laughs)

01:34.792 --> 01:36.926
I posted a picture on Instagram,
and it got 200 likes.

01:36.927 --> 01:38.928
Yeah, way to be at one with nature.

01:38.929 --> 01:40.496
ALISON: You're just
jealous because people

01:40.497 --> 01:42.406
- actually care what I'm doing.
- Look, your friends

01:42.407 --> 01:43.933
looked at your photo and
then tapped it twice.

01:43.934 --> 01:45.501
Look out, Taylor Swift.

01:45.502 --> 01:47.103
Okay, everybody, to the barn.

01:47.104 --> 01:48.271
You guys feed them, rub them down,

01:48.272 --> 01:50.106
and then muck out the stalls, all right?

01:50.107 --> 01:51.174
- It's freezing.
- Come on.

01:51.175 --> 01:52.375
Please, can we do it after?

01:52.376 --> 01:54.074
- No.
- STEVIE: Not a chance.

01:54.075 --> 01:56.045
She loves these horses
more than she loves us.

01:56.046 --> 01:57.480
Because they don't talk back.

01:57.481 --> 01:58.948
- What is...?
- (groans)

01:58.949 --> 02:00.783
ELIZABETH: What are they doing?
They're not supposed to be here

02:00.784 --> 02:01.918
for another three hours.

02:01.919 --> 02:03.519
The cell reception is terrible.

02:03.520 --> 02:05.521
- Well, that's another reason we should...
- Stop!

02:05.522 --> 02:07.156
NADINE: Sorry to interrupt, ma'am.

02:07.157 --> 02:09.125
Sorry!

02:09.126 --> 02:10.693
We've been calling since this morning,

02:10.693 --> 02:12.562
but, uh, we didn't have any signal.

02:12.563 --> 02:13.696
What is that smell?

02:13.697 --> 02:15.031
NADINE: We have good news.

02:15.032 --> 02:16.732
They reached an agreement in Brussels

02:16.733 --> 02:18.234
to solve the Greek debt crisis.

02:18.235 --> 02:20.390
Oh, thank God! And horse crap.

02:20.391 --> 02:21.871
I beg your pardon?

02:21.872 --> 02:23.339
That's what that smell is.

02:23.340 --> 02:26.578
- Oh. - HENRY: Well, another
global depression avoided.

02:26.579 --> 02:27.572
- Lunch?
- NADINE: Thank you.

02:27.573 --> 02:28.773
But we really need to get going.

02:28.774 --> 02:31.676
Russell Jackson's been
calling all morning.

02:31.677 --> 02:33.912
Well, that is until we lost our signals.

02:33.913 --> 02:35.580
The president wants to see you, ma'am.

02:35.581 --> 02:38.316
I'm sure it's about the Brussels trip.

02:38.317 --> 02:39.784
Sorry, would you mind
if I used your bathroom

02:39.785 --> 02:41.019
before we get going?

02:41.020 --> 02:43.387
- Yeah.
- Yeah, any place behind the barn is fine.

02:46.091 --> 02:48.193
Oh, ha-ha. Mock the city mouse.

02:48.194 --> 02:50.395
QUINN: <i>The Greeks are acting
like spoiled children.</i>

02:50.396 --> 02:53.031
They don't like spending cuts.
They don't want to be audited.

02:53.032 --> 02:56.067
As if they earned the right
to dictate terms to anyone.

02:56.068 --> 02:57.569
Come in, Elizabeth.

02:57.570 --> 03:00.305
You know the former Treasury Secretary.

03:00.306 --> 03:01.339
Of course. Hey, Max.

03:01.340 --> 03:03.108
How's life in the private sector?

03:03.109 --> 03:04.376
(chuckles) Peachy.

03:04.377 --> 03:05.577
Until today.

03:05.578 --> 03:07.779
Our old friend is sharing his opinion

03:07.780 --> 03:09.748
of the Greek financial
agreement we brokered.

03:09.749 --> 03:11.916
- Ah.
- QUINN: The short version is

03:11.917 --> 03:14.552
my hedge fund's investors
are getting shafted.

03:14.553 --> 03:16.021
- You see an alternative?
- Absolutely!

03:16.022 --> 03:18.490
Insist on additional austerity measures.

03:18.491 --> 03:21.159
Make the Greeks accountable
for the promises they made.

03:21.160 --> 03:22.694
I wish we could, but the Greek economy

03:22.695 --> 03:23.762
is on the verge of collapse.

03:23.763 --> 03:25.263
Believe me, this is
the best we could do.

03:25.264 --> 03:26.264
I doubt that.

03:26.265 --> 03:27.899
Sir, letting the Greeks

03:27.900 --> 03:30.101
off the hook will set
a terrible precedent.

03:30.102 --> 03:32.303
You'll erode confidence
in the entire bond market.

03:32.304 --> 03:35.006
And if the Greeks
default, we're looking at

03:35.007 --> 03:36.307
worldwide panic.

03:36.308 --> 03:38.143
There won't be a bond market left.

03:38.144 --> 03:40.311
<i>If</i> they default. Mr. President,

03:40.312 --> 03:43.214
there is still time
to do the right thing.

03:43.215 --> 03:45.316
I strongly recommend that
you scuttle this agreement

03:45.317 --> 03:47.252
and get tough with the Greeks.

03:47.253 --> 03:50.288
A restructure closer to
50 cents on the dollar.

03:50.289 --> 03:52.257
I appreciate your counsel, Max.

03:52.258 --> 03:54.125
But it's a done deal.

03:54.126 --> 03:55.727
I suggest you get your
hedge fund in line.

03:55.728 --> 03:58.329
Better to get some fraction
of your investment back

03:58.330 --> 04:00.832
than nothing at all.

04:00.833 --> 04:02.634
What a waste of time.

04:02.635 --> 04:05.103
Your anti-business stance

04:05.104 --> 04:08.406
is not gonna serve you
in the next election, comrade.

04:08.407 --> 04:10.240
Mark my words.

04:15.680 --> 04:17.082
Funny, isn't it?

04:17.083 --> 04:20.218
How these courtesy meetings never are.

04:20.219 --> 04:21.519
I can't make everybody happy.

04:21.519 --> 04:24.422
Mr. President, you have made
most of Europe very happy

04:24.423 --> 04:25.924
with this agreement.

04:25.925 --> 04:27.092
Which is why I'm recommending

04:27.093 --> 04:28.393
that you make the trip to Brussels

04:28.394 --> 04:30.361
- to sign the deal.
- It's not the best time.

04:30.362 --> 04:32.430
Actually, it's the perfect time.

04:32.431 --> 04:33.565
It's a victory lap.

04:33.566 --> 04:35.266
- And you need one.
- I agree.

04:35.267 --> 04:36.367
I think you should go.

04:36.368 --> 04:37.769
You show up in Brussels,

04:37.770 --> 04:39.771
the other world leaders
won't be able to stay away.

04:39.772 --> 04:41.272
Makes it clear the world economy is

04:41.273 --> 04:43.441
being scrutinized at the highest levels.

04:43.442 --> 04:46.044
And the optics will be good
for my polling numbers.

04:46.045 --> 04:47.846
I'm not apologizing for that.

04:47.847 --> 04:49.314
After everything with Iran...

04:49.315 --> 04:50.748
It's a big win.

04:50.749 --> 04:53.283
And you need to put
yourself in front of it.

04:55.753 --> 04:57.422
Who would bring in

04:57.423 --> 05:01.926
this salt-coated,
saturated-fat-loaded, super...

05:01.927 --> 05:03.628
My mother.

05:03.629 --> 05:05.663
...delicious and satisfying snack.

05:05.664 --> 05:07.732
I bring it here so I won't eat it.

05:07.733 --> 05:09.234
You could just throw it away.

05:09.235 --> 05:10.235
I can't!

05:10.236 --> 05:12.504
I deal with people
in starving countries.

05:12.505 --> 05:14.205
I agree that it's wrong
to throw away food,

05:14.206 --> 05:16.374
but what does that
have to do with this?

05:16.375 --> 05:18.343
Are we having our first
cute workplace fight?

05:18.344 --> 05:20.044
- No, we're just talking.
- Aw.

05:20.045 --> 05:22.046
I think we are. I think we
should mark the occasion.

05:22.047 --> 05:23.195
- Are you crazy? Stop it!
- "Crazy"?

05:23.196 --> 05:24.149
Someone's gonna walk in.

05:24.150 --> 05:26.050
- I'm a moderate risk taker.
- (phone chimes)

05:26.051 --> 05:28.620
Oh, you've got to be kidding me.

05:28.621 --> 05:30.221
Everything okay?

05:30.222 --> 05:32.757
It's my magical disappearing friend.

05:32.758 --> 05:33.791
(chuckles)

05:33.792 --> 05:35.260
Everybody has one.

05:35.261 --> 05:36.561
Seriously.

05:36.562 --> 05:37.896
We knew each other as kids.

05:37.897 --> 05:40.765
We were really close friends
in high school, and then

05:40.766 --> 05:42.467
he just became a swooper, you know?

05:42.468 --> 05:45.837
Don't hear from him for ages,
then he swoops in and asks,

05:45.838 --> 05:47.539
"Why aren't we hanging out anymore?"

05:47.540 --> 05:48.706
- So he's back?
- Yeah.

05:48.707 --> 05:50.141
As if nothing ever happened.

05:50.142 --> 05:53.011
"Want to have lunch with me
at my house today, Ginjy".

05:53.012 --> 05:54.646
- "Ginjy"?
- Yeah.

05:54.647 --> 05:55.914
Ginger head. It...

05:55.915 --> 05:57.348
It's, like, an inside joke.

05:57.349 --> 05:59.117
- He's colorblind.
- He's-he's a guy?

05:59.118 --> 06:01.019
Yeah.

06:01.020 --> 06:04.155
An immature swooper guy
who calls me Ginjy.

06:04.156 --> 06:06.024
Go.

06:06.025 --> 06:08.292
Go have lunch with your friend.

06:14.966 --> 06:17.135
Um, I'm here to see Harrison Dalton.

06:17.136 --> 06:19.003
HARRISON: Hey! Hey.

06:19.004 --> 06:20.572
- Hey!
- You made it!

06:20.573 --> 06:21.873
- (both laugh)
- Mr. Dalton,

06:21.874 --> 06:23.341
- you really shouldn't.
- I'm sorry.

06:23.342 --> 06:25.210
Nobody cares about the president's kid.

06:25.211 --> 06:27.812
- STEVIE: Oh, my God!
- Oh, my God, it's you! Ginjy!

06:27.813 --> 06:29.280
(laughing): Wait, wait, wait, my wallet!

06:29.281 --> 06:32.115
Get your wallet.
Thank you, Brian. Sorry!

06:38.022 --> 06:39.857
Oh!

06:39.858 --> 06:41.893
(laughs)

06:41.894 --> 06:43.361
You should be way better at this.

06:43.362 --> 06:45.897
I mean, you have a bowling alley
inside of your actual house.

06:45.898 --> 06:47.402
This is temporary lodgings.

06:47.403 --> 06:49.667
I don't actually live with my
parents; that'd be pathetic.

06:49.668 --> 06:51.703
What happened to grad school?

06:51.704 --> 06:54.405
You haven't heard?

06:54.406 --> 06:57.542
I am straight out of rehab.

06:57.543 --> 07:00.511
Oh.

07:00.512 --> 07:02.714
- Uh...
- Yeah, awkward.

07:02.715 --> 07:05.383
Uh, I thought my dad told your
mom, and that you would, uh...

07:05.384 --> 07:06.417
Nope.

07:06.418 --> 07:08.820
You want to ask?

07:08.821 --> 07:10.054
- I don't want to ask.
- Ask.

07:10.055 --> 07:10.710
- I don't.
- Ask.

07:10.711 --> 07:13.258
- I don't want to ask.
- Oxy.

07:13.259 --> 07:15.026
And, yeah, I ended up
hitting the streets

07:15.027 --> 07:18.196
after that got too
expensive, and I am your...

07:18.197 --> 07:20.431
basic <i>Dr. Phil</i> episode.

07:20.432 --> 07:22.900
With the added bonus
of being the first son.

07:22.901 --> 07:24.736
(both laugh)

07:24.737 --> 07:26.638
It's amazing the old

07:26.639 --> 07:28.339
baseball cap and sunglasses disguise

07:28.340 --> 07:30.041
actually works on heroin dealers.

07:30.042 --> 07:31.009
Wow.

07:31.010 --> 07:33.478
Managed to avoid <i>TMZ.</i>

07:33.479 --> 07:35.179
You're... okay now?

07:35.180 --> 07:36.281
I'm killing it.

07:36.282 --> 07:37.881
90 meetings, 90 days.

07:38.916 --> 07:40.585
I'm good. I'm lucky.

07:40.586 --> 07:42.720
Yes, you are.

07:42.721 --> 07:44.222
And just when I thought I had run out

07:44.223 --> 07:45.490
of ways to disappoint my father.

07:45.491 --> 07:46.924
(laughs) Oh, come on.

07:46.925 --> 07:48.526
He doesn't think of you like that.

07:48.527 --> 07:50.128
He knows that it's hard being you.

07:50.129 --> 07:52.196
You are the sister I never had, Ginjy.

07:52.197 --> 07:54.165
Oh! (laughs)

07:54.166 --> 07:56.234
Fellow CIA brat who knows
what it's like to grow up

07:56.235 --> 07:58.503
in a house of secrets and lies.

07:58.504 --> 08:00.738
Well, as your honorary
sister, I think it's time

08:00.739 --> 08:03.274
that I tell you to stop talking
like you're in a Chekov play.

08:03.275 --> 08:04.676
That was the 12th step.

08:04.677 --> 08:07.145
Acknowledging that you're not
in a Russian parlor drama.

08:07.146 --> 08:08.646
Hey, I know I say this a lot,

08:08.647 --> 08:11.816
but I-I... I wish that we did this more.

08:11.817 --> 08:14.919
You know? We could be like
we used to be, only smarter

08:14.920 --> 08:15.920
and better-looking.

08:15.921 --> 08:17.388
I'm way ahead of you there.

08:17.389 --> 08:18.688
So...

08:19.957 --> 08:22.225
No! No!

08:26.898 --> 08:28.333
Extra care here, gentlemen.

08:28.334 --> 08:30.101
Let's get these beauties home to Greece

08:30.102 --> 08:32.337
with all their fingers and toes.

08:32.337 --> 08:33.705
The ones they still have anyway.

08:33.706 --> 08:35.673
We'll take them from here.

08:35.674 --> 08:36.506
Excuse me?

08:36.508 --> 08:37.909
I'm taking these statues.

08:37.909 --> 08:40.311
I have no authorization
to release these to anyone.

08:40.312 --> 08:42.113
Now you do.

08:42.114 --> 08:43.581
You see <i>Repo Man?</i>

08:43.582 --> 08:46.050
That's a court order giving
me permission to repossess

08:46.051 --> 08:49.420
the statues to pay a debt
owed by the Greek government.

08:49.421 --> 08:51.456
Call whoever you want.

08:51.457 --> 08:54.292
They're mine now.

08:54.293 --> 08:57.929
MATT: <i>"Under cover of darkness,
Global M-7 Hedge Fund owner</i>

08:57.930 --> 09:01.065
"Max Quinn pulled off the most audacious

09:01.066 --> 09:03.201
"and expensive repo of all time,

09:03.202 --> 09:07.271
seizing Greece's priceless
Spartan Figures of Democracy."

09:07.272 --> 09:08.740
Man, he just took them!

09:08.741 --> 09:10.241
He didn't even have a gun.

09:10.242 --> 09:12.377
He didn't need a gun.
He had a court order.

09:12.378 --> 09:14.345
Wonder what he used
to get the court order.

09:14.346 --> 09:15.546
He's the former treasury secretary.

09:15.547 --> 09:17.515
He used his cell phone.

09:17.516 --> 09:20.284
The Greeks have owed him
$1.3 billion for ten years.

09:20.285 --> 09:21.753
Those same Greeks are

09:21.754 --> 09:22.987
rioting in the streets to protest

09:22.988 --> 09:24.188
the seizure of their artwork.

09:24.189 --> 09:25.308
MATT: Yeah, what do you expect?

09:25.309 --> 09:26.657
They break plates when they're happy.

09:26.658 --> 09:27.507
It's more than that.

09:27.508 --> 09:29.961
You can't put a price on the
Spartan Figures of Democracy.

09:29.962 --> 09:31.729
It would be like someone stealing

09:31.730 --> 09:33.231
the Declaration of Independence.

09:33.232 --> 09:35.166
Social media is totally behind Quinn.

09:35.167 --> 09:37.468
They're hailing him as a
modern-day Jesse James.

09:37.469 --> 09:40.505
The outlaw, not Sandra
Bullock's ex-husband.

09:40.506 --> 09:44.375
Hey, has anyone pointed out that
Sparta was not a democracy?

09:44.376 --> 09:46.978
I mean, it was a totally
militarized society.

09:46.979 --> 09:48.479
They were misnamed by
a British explorer,

09:48.480 --> 09:49.981
who originally stole
them from the Greeks

09:49.982 --> 09:51.182
back in the 19th century.

09:51.183 --> 09:53.184
They've had a hard life.

09:53.185 --> 09:55.887
They're like the foster
children of antiquities.

09:55.888 --> 09:57.455
And we want them to be happy.

09:57.456 --> 09:59.123
But right now, we need to focus

09:59.124 --> 10:01.592
on the economic summit in Brussels.

10:01.593 --> 10:03.528
I'd like to lay some guidelines.

10:03.529 --> 10:05.430
Oh, here we go.

10:05.431 --> 10:06.864
I beg your pardon?

10:06.865 --> 10:07.999
Hmm?

10:08.000 --> 10:09.901
Oh, I didn't realize
I said that out loud.

10:09.902 --> 10:10.835
(snorts)

10:10.836 --> 10:12.837
It's just that...

10:12.838 --> 10:15.206
you're always so...

10:15.207 --> 10:18.376
thorough... in prepping us

10:18.377 --> 10:21.245
about the pitfalls of fraternizing

10:21.246 --> 10:23.080
with the staffs of other countries.

10:23.081 --> 10:24.348
This trip is different.

10:24.349 --> 10:26.818
The summit has a reputation
for being a party conference.

10:26.819 --> 10:28.085
Everything is pre-negotiated.

10:28.086 --> 10:29.487
JAY: Which means some down time

10:29.488 --> 10:30.688
for us staffers!

10:30.689 --> 10:33.558
Hey, look, personally, I'd watch out

10:33.559 --> 10:34.926
for the Swedish delegation

10:34.927 --> 10:37.628
and their endless supply of aquavit.

10:37.629 --> 10:39.030
Actually, it was the Spaniards

10:39.031 --> 10:41.532
with their under-appreciated
regional wines and olive skin

10:41.533 --> 10:43.568
that had me hugging the porcelain.

10:43.569 --> 10:45.136
I'm quite serious about this.

10:45.137 --> 10:48.306
We've taken some very public blows lately.

10:48.307 --> 10:51.408
Just... behave yourselves.

10:54.946 --> 10:56.414
(door closes)

10:56.415 --> 10:58.382
Those statues were on their
way back to the Greeks,

10:58.383 --> 11:01.752
who so generously allowed
us to display them here.

11:01.753 --> 11:04.856
So you can see how embarrassing this is.

11:04.857 --> 11:08.626
Madam Secretary, do you know
what an economy runs on?

11:08.627 --> 11:09.727
Confidence.

11:09.728 --> 11:11.362
Really? I was gonna say money.

11:11.363 --> 11:13.965
When you issue a bond,
you're selling a promise.

11:13.966 --> 11:17.268
Break that promise, and
fear rules the market.

11:17.269 --> 11:19.170
I'm just holding the Greeks accountable.

11:19.171 --> 11:21.305
You're holding their prized
antiquities hostage.

11:21.306 --> 11:22.907
You can't possibly sell them.

11:22.908 --> 11:24.208
(laughs): Of course not.

11:24.209 --> 11:25.309
They're priceless.

11:25.310 --> 11:26.944
Well, then what do you want?

11:26.945 --> 11:28.880
What any reasonable investor wants.

11:28.881 --> 11:30.815
No, because all the other
reasonable investors

11:30.816 --> 11:32.016
are signing the debt deal.

11:32.017 --> 11:33.017
And they're welcome to.

11:33.018 --> 11:36.354
Me? I'm gonna get paid in full.

11:36.355 --> 11:38.422
Max, that is never gonna happen.

11:38.423 --> 11:40.458
You got to give me something
that I can work with.

11:40.459 --> 11:41.459
And send a message

11:41.460 --> 11:43.528
that corrupt, incompetent governments

11:43.529 --> 11:45.496
can spend their way into oblivion

11:45.497 --> 11:47.832
and count on us to pick up the pieces?

11:47.833 --> 11:48.833
Someone's got to say no.

11:48.834 --> 11:50.601
Even if it means a black eye

11:50.602 --> 11:52.670
for your country and your president?

11:52.671 --> 11:54.305
That's what I'm counting on.

11:54.306 --> 11:55.973
(dial tone)

11:55.974 --> 11:57.240
(hangs up phone)

12:00.279 --> 12:06.729
Subtitle sync and corrections
by awaqeded for www.addic7ed.com.

12:11.044 --> 12:12.579
(door opens)

12:12.580 --> 12:13.880
I hear you didn't get very far

12:13.881 --> 12:15.482
with the former treasury secretary.

12:15.483 --> 12:16.883
Russell, do come in.

12:16.884 --> 12:19.152
Let's put a lock on that door, Blake.

12:19.153 --> 12:20.120
Maybe a Marine guard.

12:20.121 --> 12:21.588
Yes, ma'am.

12:21.589 --> 12:23.556
Did you really think I
was gonna convince Quinn

12:23.557 --> 12:25.058
to give the statues back?

12:25.059 --> 12:26.159
A guy could hope.

12:26.160 --> 12:27.394
You're welcome to use the phone.

12:27.395 --> 12:29.029
Which works with me, too, by the way.

12:29.030 --> 12:29.996
I just left the Hill.

12:29.997 --> 12:31.297
I thought I'd make a pit stop.

12:31.298 --> 12:33.166
I wanted to let you know

12:33.167 --> 12:36.569
that I will not be making
the Brussels trip, so...

12:36.570 --> 12:38.438
make sure everything
goes according to plan.

12:38.439 --> 12:39.973
- No screw-ups.
- I'll do my best.

12:39.974 --> 12:41.374
After the Munsey scandal,

12:41.375 --> 12:44.644
people either think the
president was involved or weak

12:44.645 --> 12:46.279
not to have known something.

12:46.280 --> 12:48.515
The only thing we have
to rebuild his stature

12:48.516 --> 12:51.151
is the economy.

12:51.152 --> 12:52.819
So why aren't you going?

12:52.820 --> 12:54.854
'Cause somebody's got to
hit the talk show circuit

12:54.855 --> 12:56.956
about these damn statues.

12:56.957 --> 12:59.993
Clearly, I'm the one with
the most on-air personality.

12:59.994 --> 13:01.261
Yeah.

13:01.262 --> 13:04.297
You do have a kind of... stealthy charm.

13:04.298 --> 13:05.732
Yeah, well, let's hope so.

13:05.733 --> 13:08.134
Because it also turns out
there's a lot of cleanup

13:08.135 --> 13:09.602
after a failed coup.

13:09.603 --> 13:13.873
So I'll be Al Haig-ing it while
POTUS is victory-lapping.

13:13.874 --> 13:15.241
And you

13:15.242 --> 13:17.177
have to be flawless.

13:17.178 --> 13:18.278
Skate a clean program.

13:18.279 --> 13:20.380
I'm sharpening my blades.

13:20.381 --> 13:22.614
Tight turns.

13:28.621 --> 13:31.191
These are the four criteria
of the right to go to war,

13:31.192 --> 13:32.459
as outlined by the author

13:32.460 --> 13:36.129
of the just war theory
in Western tradition.

13:36.130 --> 13:39.632
Who was none other than...?

13:39.633 --> 13:41.534
Anybody? No one?

13:41.535 --> 13:42.469
Saint Augustine.

13:42.470 --> 13:44.003
- Come on.
- (students chuckle)

13:44.004 --> 13:45.705
I know it seems like a big contradiction

13:45.706 --> 13:48.675
for a holy man to take
on the issue of warfare

13:48.676 --> 13:51.845
in such a pragmatic way,
but most religious traditions

13:51.846 --> 13:53.713
address the matter in a similar fashion.

13:53.714 --> 13:55.247
There's only...

13:56.783 --> 13:59.018
...a handful of religious traditions

13:59.019 --> 14:01.087
that eschew the notion
of war altogether.

14:01.088 --> 14:03.356
Most take the position
that it's inevitable

14:03.357 --> 14:07.327
and therefore must
strive to be... moral.

14:07.328 --> 14:11.164
Or as my own military
ethics professor once said,

14:11.165 --> 14:14.200
"War is always wrong.

14:14.201 --> 14:16.703
"Always.

14:16.704 --> 14:18.404
But some things are wronger."

14:18.405 --> 14:19.806
(students chuckle)

14:19.807 --> 14:22.275
Okay, that's it for today. Thank you.

14:22.276 --> 14:24.677
Good-bye.

14:24.678 --> 14:26.946
(students talking quietly)

14:26.947 --> 14:28.014
Dr. McCord.

14:28.015 --> 14:29.549
Yes?

14:29.550 --> 14:31.684
Brigadier General Mitch Sarno.

14:31.685 --> 14:32.685
Great lecture.

14:32.686 --> 14:34.687
Well, you just saw the end of it.

14:34.688 --> 14:36.422
Uh, what can I do for you, General?

14:36.423 --> 14:38.224
I've been following your
military ethics courses

14:38.225 --> 14:39.626
since you were at UVA.

14:39.627 --> 14:42.729
We take an interest in
how the next generation

14:42.730 --> 14:45.265
is being instructed along those lines.

14:45.266 --> 14:46.599
"We"?

14:46.600 --> 14:48.434
I'm sorry, I thought you
might be aware of my work.

14:48.435 --> 14:49.602
I'm the commandant of

14:49.603 --> 14:51.838
the National War College here in D.C.

14:51.839 --> 14:54.240
Well, I'm flattered that
you're interested in me,

14:54.241 --> 14:55.808
and a little paranoid. (chuckles)

14:55.809 --> 14:57.677
It's a scouting mission.

14:57.678 --> 14:59.379
We think

14:59.380 --> 15:00.513
you'd fit nicely in

15:00.514 --> 15:03.616
our Strategic Studies department.

15:03.617 --> 15:04.918
You're offering me a job?

15:04.919 --> 15:07.787
You'd be a strong
addition to our faculty.

15:07.788 --> 15:10.523
Well, uh... that-that's
quite an honor, General,

15:10.524 --> 15:12.659
but, um, I'm happy with what I do here.

15:12.660 --> 15:14.627
Yes, it is rewarding,

15:14.628 --> 15:16.763
shaping the minds of
liberal arts students.

15:16.764 --> 15:18.698
But our students

15:18.699 --> 15:20.033
need to understand

15:20.034 --> 15:22.769
the beliefs and customs
of a potential enemy.

15:22.770 --> 15:25.772
You would be teaching all the future

15:25.773 --> 15:28.174
military and national security leaders.

15:28.175 --> 15:29.943
And working for the Defense Department.

15:29.944 --> 15:32.245
If you're worried about
a conflict of interest,

15:32.246 --> 15:33.913
we're not.

15:33.914 --> 15:37.115
It all falls under the
dome of national security.

15:39.919 --> 15:41.853
Give it some thought.

15:47.860 --> 15:50.363
Harrison...

15:50.364 --> 15:53.433
I've called twice and I've texted twice,

15:53.434 --> 15:55.068
because I really kicked

15:55.069 --> 15:57.337
the "I want to see you more" football.

15:57.338 --> 15:59.606
But now I am starting
to feel like an idiot.

15:59.607 --> 16:00.873
And a stalker.

16:00.874 --> 16:02.609
So I'm not gonna call you again.

16:02.610 --> 16:04.743
Ball's in your court.

16:05.445 --> 16:06.813
Let me guess.

16:06.814 --> 16:08.081
I'm an idiot.

16:08.082 --> 16:09.282
I'm telling you.

16:09.283 --> 16:10.984
It's a character defect. You can't engage.

16:10.985 --> 16:12.352
I have to try though.

16:12.353 --> 16:14.921
I mean, he... he's in a
really fragile state.

16:14.922 --> 16:17.657
He's just been through
a really, really hard time.

16:17.658 --> 16:18.858
Rehab?

16:18.859 --> 16:20.426
I didn't say that.

16:20.427 --> 16:21.594
You don't have to.

16:21.595 --> 16:23.963
The disappearing act is
classic addict behavior.

16:23.964 --> 16:25.031
People get better.

16:25.032 --> 16:26.833
Not by being enabled.

16:26.834 --> 16:28.568
Which is what you're doing
if you're chasing him around

16:28.569 --> 16:30.536
to hold his hand and
listen to his feelings.

16:30.537 --> 16:33.039
It's just... you don't
know what it's like

16:33.040 --> 16:36.641
to be in a family like his family.

16:37.377 --> 16:39.279
I know who his family is.

16:39.280 --> 16:41.014
I heard you say "Harrison".

16:41.015 --> 16:42.515
I have some deductive reasoning skills.

16:42.516 --> 16:43.916
Okay, well, please don't tell anybody.

16:43.917 --> 16:46.185
Everybody knows he's troubled.

16:46.186 --> 16:49.121
The press is gonna get ahold
of the rehab thing eventually.

16:49.889 --> 16:51.758
Hey.

16:51.759 --> 16:55.093
No matter what happens,
you're not responsible.

16:59.065 --> 17:00.800
Ow! Ow...

17:00.801 --> 17:02.335
- Ah, damn it!
- HENRY: Are you okay?

17:02.336 --> 17:03.703
- What just happened?
- Will you please

17:03.704 --> 17:05.738
sit on my suitcase while I close it?

17:05.739 --> 17:07.205
Will you say that again,

17:07.207 --> 17:09.541
- in a slow, sexy voice?
- Come on.

17:09.542 --> 17:12.044
Okay. Do you really need all
this stuff for a three-day trip?

17:12.045 --> 17:13.112
It's Europe.

17:13.113 --> 17:14.681
They're judgy.

17:14.682 --> 17:16.082
Hey, are you sure you're okay with this?

17:16.083 --> 17:17.483
It's the first time
you've been abroad since,

17:17.483 --> 17:19.452
- you know, all that...
- Yes, I am fine.

17:19.453 --> 17:22.755
Look, I've got my unopened
bottle of nerve pills,

17:22.756 --> 17:27.894
and I've got 15 hours of
whale songs on my iPad

17:27.895 --> 17:30.630
and a brown paper bag
that I can breathe into.

17:30.631 --> 17:31.764
Really,

17:31.765 --> 17:32.999
I am fine. I promise.

17:33.000 --> 17:34.667
And I've been doing that
meditation every day,

17:34.668 --> 17:36.002
which I know is working

17:36.003 --> 17:37.603
because of how much I hate it.

17:37.604 --> 17:38.871
- Well, good.
- Hey, listen.

17:38.872 --> 17:40.039
I know it goes without saying,

17:40.040 --> 17:42.075
but you are not going to accept that job

17:42.076 --> 17:43.810
without a full-on family meeting, right?

17:43.811 --> 17:45.878
I will go you one better.

17:45.879 --> 17:47.880
(sighs) I'm not going
to accept that job.

17:47.881 --> 17:50.717
What? You're... you're not
even gonna consider it?

17:50.718 --> 17:54.087
A religious scholar teaching
at the National War College?

17:54.088 --> 17:56.522
There's only so much cognitive
dissonance I can handle.

17:56.523 --> 17:57.690
Teaching military ethics,

17:57.691 --> 18:00.626
a subject that you happen
to be passionate about.

18:00.627 --> 18:02.128
Okay. I don't want to work

18:02.129 --> 18:03.529
for a competing
department of government.

18:03.530 --> 18:05.932
State and Defense don't compete.

18:05.933 --> 18:08.101
We compare and contrast expertise,

18:08.102 --> 18:11.437
often in an openly hostile manner.

18:11.438 --> 18:14.440
Babe, I am happy where I am, really.

18:14.441 --> 18:16.275
W-Wait, what is this?

18:16.276 --> 18:18.044
What is this?

18:18.045 --> 18:20.146
GEORGIOU: ...a series of insults

18:20.147 --> 18:22.348
from foreign governments,

18:22.349 --> 18:25.585
- and the loss of a national treasure,
- (phone vibrating)

18:25.586 --> 18:27.587
we must reject

18:27.588 --> 18:30.189
the negotiated debt deal in Brussels.

18:30.190 --> 18:31.624
(phone continues vibrating)

18:31.625 --> 18:33.326
That can't be good.

18:33.327 --> 18:35.561
Hey, Russell.

18:35.562 --> 18:36.829
Yeah.

18:36.830 --> 18:38.431
I'm finding out the same way you are.

18:38.432 --> 18:40.299
I'll get into it.

18:40.300 --> 18:42.935
(sighs)

18:42.936 --> 18:44.537
So...

18:44.538 --> 18:46.606
unless we can convince Greece

18:46.607 --> 18:50.243
to make a new deal, and fast,
they're gonna default.

18:50.244 --> 18:53.311
Leading to global economic collapse.

18:54.847 --> 18:57.617
We are not finished talking
about your job offer.

18:57.618 --> 18:59.452
Why don't you concentrate

18:59.453 --> 19:01.554
on making sure our 401(k)s and house

19:01.555 --> 19:03.555
aren't worthless by tomorrow morning?

