19:35.154 --> 19:38.257
Seems our victory lap has
turned into a funeral march.

19:38.258 --> 19:41.126
There is a definite chill in the air.

19:42.862 --> 19:44.997
And here comes the German chancellor.

19:44.998 --> 19:47.333
Even at her most chipper,
she can freeze fire.

19:47.334 --> 19:50.336
Chancellor Schulz. Glad to see you.

19:50.337 --> 19:54.073
I had hoped our circumstances
would be more celebratory.

19:54.074 --> 19:55.875
Yes.

19:55.876 --> 19:57.577
It is my understanding

19:57.578 --> 20:00.046
that the man responsible
for this catastrophe

20:00.047 --> 20:02.114
is a cabinet member of your choosing,

20:02.115 --> 20:03.549
Mr. President.

20:03.550 --> 20:06.185
Max Quinn is a former
cabinet member, Chancellor.

20:06.186 --> 20:08.988
But appointed by your
president, Madam Secretary.

20:08.989 --> 20:10.389
You are absolutely correct.

20:10.390 --> 20:13.993
But the true catastrophe began
with our friends, the Greeks.

20:13.994 --> 20:16.128
Why don't we concentrate
on getting them back on board

20:16.129 --> 20:18.598
with the debt deal that we
all worked so hard for?

20:18.599 --> 20:19.966
The Greeks have made it clear

20:19.967 --> 20:22.068
that without their prized antiquities,

20:22.069 --> 20:23.936
they have no interest.

20:23.937 --> 20:27.340
I can assure you that Secretary
McCord is working on a solution.

20:27.341 --> 20:29.642
We all know that without
a sound financial plan,

20:29.643 --> 20:31.077
everyone's economy is in peril.

20:31.078 --> 20:32.411
And that is why the Greeks

20:32.412 --> 20:35.047
must get their precious statues
as quickly as possible.

20:35.048 --> 20:36.215
Perhaps if you and I can get

20:36.216 --> 20:37.650
Prime Minister Georgiou to meet with...

20:37.651 --> 20:39.352
Frankly, Mr. President,

20:39.353 --> 20:43.556
Europe is no longer
interested in American help.

20:43.557 --> 20:46.259
We must solve this on our own.

20:46.260 --> 20:48.093
Please excuse me.

20:52.031 --> 20:54.500
Did she just dis-invite us to the party?

20:54.501 --> 20:56.135
Tell me you're on this, Bess.

20:56.136 --> 20:58.403
I am on this, sir.

21:06.483 --> 21:08.659
NADINE: <i>That's not just
Georgiou making a stand</i>

21:08.660 --> 21:10.527
because Quinn took their statues.

21:10.528 --> 21:12.600
Everyone is mad at us
because of this debacle.

21:12.601 --> 21:14.335
The Greeks are leading
the world to the edge

21:14.336 --> 21:16.070
of financial collapse, and
the United States is blamed?

21:16.071 --> 21:17.371
MATT: That's why the French never

21:17.372 --> 21:19.407
texted me back about their party.

21:19.408 --> 21:20.675
Seriously?

21:20.676 --> 21:23.177
That guidelines discussion
just never lands, does it?

21:23.178 --> 21:24.478
It's a friendship summit.

21:24.479 --> 21:26.480
Camaraderie is diplomacy.

21:26.481 --> 21:28.215
I just got off the phone
with the attorney general.

21:28.216 --> 21:29.784
She's filing an emergency stay

21:29.785 --> 21:31.152
with the D.C. Court of Appeals,

21:31.153 --> 21:32.687
but we won't get a ruling until Monday.

21:32.688 --> 21:33.654
At which point...

21:33.655 --> 21:35.423
Greece will already be in default.

21:35.424 --> 21:37.458
I need a quick fix... something, anyone.

21:37.459 --> 21:38.993
JAY: I've been back
channeling with the IMF.

21:38.994 --> 21:40.294
Seeing if they're willing to make

21:40.295 --> 21:42.263
an emergency loan to buy
the Greeks more time.

21:42.264 --> 21:43.531
All right. Stay on them.

21:43.532 --> 21:45.132
In the meantime, ask the
European Central Bank

21:45.133 --> 21:47.301
if they'll look into another
bond restructuring.

21:47.302 --> 21:50.037
What else? I need something on Quinn.

21:50.038 --> 21:51.372
Something I can use for leverage.

21:51.373 --> 21:53.507
Payroll taxes, IRS.

21:53.508 --> 21:54.642
The man can't be squeaky clean.

21:54.643 --> 21:56.344
And the judge who
issued the court order.

21:56.345 --> 21:57.745
That couldn't have been the most

21:57.746 --> 21:58.713
pristine legal process.

21:58.714 --> 22:00.147
NADINE: My concern, ma'am,

22:00.148 --> 22:01.515
is that investigations take time,

22:01.516 --> 22:03.150
and this summit is over in two days.

22:03.151 --> 22:04.452
Noted.

22:04.453 --> 22:06.187
But we have to at least try.

22:06.188 --> 22:07.822
So, dig in.

22:07.823 --> 22:09.223
Blake, walk with me.

22:09.224 --> 22:11.758
I have something I need you to do.

22:15.062 --> 22:16.464
Prime Minster Georgiou, I assure you,

22:16.465 --> 22:18.566
we are doing everything we can

22:18.567 --> 22:20.501
to get you your statues back.

22:20.502 --> 22:23.771
But the best thing you can do
for your people and the world

22:23.772 --> 22:24.772
is to accept this agreement.

22:24.773 --> 22:26.507
Let's sign it, and get your country

22:26.508 --> 22:28.509
back on firm financial footing.

22:28.510 --> 22:32.012
So, we loan you national treasure,

22:32.013 --> 22:35.116
and in return, we suffer no less

22:35.117 --> 22:38.419
than an act of piracy on your land.

22:38.420 --> 22:40.287
DALTON: You have my word,

22:40.288 --> 22:41.889
your antiquities will be returned to you.

22:41.890 --> 22:43.991
But it will take time.

22:43.992 --> 22:46.127
The world economy is on
a precipice right now.

22:46.128 --> 22:49.997
We're asking you to think
of the lives of your people.

22:49.998 --> 22:52.366
I am! As prime minister,

22:52.367 --> 22:55.403
I have to make this stand
for the sake of my people.

22:55.404 --> 22:58.372
National pride... (chuckles)

22:58.373 --> 22:59.940
is at an all-time low.

22:59.941 --> 23:03.210
And how will economic collapse
affect national pride?

23:03.211 --> 23:04.478
What's your endgame?

23:04.479 --> 23:07.782
Spiros, sometimes we have to
bear the brunt of criticism

23:07.783 --> 23:10.718
for a more profitable
and enduring outcome.

23:10.719 --> 23:13.254
Please, don't... lecture me, Conrad.

23:13.255 --> 23:17.091
Maybe if you had listened
to your citizens,

23:17.092 --> 23:19.527
your own party would not be asking you

23:19.528 --> 23:21.362
to withdraw from the next election.

23:21.363 --> 23:24.365
The Iran debacle, the
corruption of your CIA...

23:24.366 --> 23:27.968
your credibility was the real casualty.

23:27.969 --> 23:33.007
If you actually cared
about the world economy,

23:33.008 --> 23:35.441
you wouldn't wait until the election.

23:37.244 --> 23:40.414
You would resign now.

23:40.415 --> 23:43.082
We have nothing more to discuss.

23:51.292 --> 23:53.060
Ooh, the cauliflower looks good.

23:53.061 --> 23:54.261
And the beets.

23:54.262 --> 23:56.764
And I'm-I'm totally
down with the escarole.

23:56.765 --> 23:58.432
You don't have to do this.

23:58.433 --> 23:59.767
You should order whatever you want.

23:59.768 --> 24:01.769
No, it's okay. I'm an aspiring vegan.

24:01.770 --> 24:03.204
Well, I'm getting tired of it.

24:03.205 --> 24:04.472
You want to let eggs back in?

24:04.473 --> 24:06.774
No, I want to let bacon burgers back in.

24:06.775 --> 24:07.975
Yeah, you'll get over it.

24:07.976 --> 24:09.777
No, I'm dreaming about them.

24:09.778 --> 24:11.312
Is that why I keep waking up

24:11.313 --> 24:13.414
with my head between two pillows?

24:13.415 --> 24:14.582
Whoa, sorry...

24:14.583 --> 24:17.084
Excuse me, uh, could you
turn that up, please?

24:17.085 --> 24:19.854
...House officials are reporting
that an ambulance was called

24:19.855 --> 24:22.723
by someone in the White House
for a member of the staff.

24:22.724 --> 24:25.693
We're told it was a
non-life-threatening emergency.

24:25.694 --> 24:28.095
And, of course, the president
is out of the country,

24:28.096 --> 24:30.431
attending an economic
summit in Brussels.

24:30.432 --> 24:31.999
Okay, that scares me.

24:32.000 --> 24:32.967
Harrison?

24:32.968 --> 24:34.401
Yeah, I haven't heard from him.

24:34.402 --> 24:36.235
They said a member of the staff.

24:36.937 --> 24:40.007
I know... (sighs)

24:40.008 --> 24:42.276
IMF and the Central European Bank

24:42.277 --> 24:44.545
are reviewing our petitions,
but no love, so far.

24:44.546 --> 24:46.947
Also, I tried to get the Germans
to sweeten the deal for Greece,

24:46.948 --> 24:48.215
but they're not budging.

24:48.216 --> 24:50.316
They're punishing them for walking out.

24:51.285 --> 24:53.220
Where's Blake?

24:53.221 --> 24:54.989
Oh, I saw him in the
lobby two hours ago,

24:54.990 --> 24:56.023
talking to some staffers.

24:56.024 --> 24:56.991
Not our people.

24:56.992 --> 24:58.659
I didn't take him for a partier.

24:58.660 --> 25:00.594
He's probably in the gym,
cycling to Sondheim.

25:00.595 --> 25:01.862
I'm gonna go find him.

25:01.863 --> 25:03.597
Nobody leaves this room.

25:03.598 --> 25:05.099
The secretary is counting on us.

25:05.100 --> 25:06.771
We will not let her down.

25:06.883 --> 25:09.303
ELIZABETH: I've been talking
to the French and Brits.

25:09.304 --> 25:10.571
If we can't get the statues,

25:10.572 --> 25:12.540
I think that we can tempt
Prime Minister Georgiou

25:12.541 --> 25:13.841
with a better debt deal.

25:13.842 --> 25:16.443
Fine.

25:16.444 --> 25:20.214
Look, I've heard about
the rumblings in the party.

25:20.215 --> 25:23.284
But did somebody really ask you
not to run for a second term?

25:23.285 --> 25:25.819
My top bundlers are
pulling their support.

25:25.820 --> 25:27.588
When the money dries up,

25:27.589 --> 25:30.090
the party looks for someone
to throw overboard.

25:30.091 --> 25:32.293
Well, we won't listen to them.

25:32.294 --> 25:34.762
Part of doing the job is knowing
when you're not doing it.

25:34.763 --> 25:36.502
Whatever happens though,
you'll keep your post.

25:36.503 --> 25:37.865
They need you, and they know it.

25:37.866 --> 25:40.000
I never wanted to be Secretary of State.

25:40.001 --> 25:41.335
I'm here because of you.

25:41.336 --> 25:42.970
Well, you should rethink your position.

25:42.971 --> 25:44.405
What is going on?

25:44.406 --> 25:47.107
Conrad, we have been in much
tougher spots than this before.

25:47.108 --> 25:48.142
Kosovo?

25:48.143 --> 25:49.877
For God sakes, 9/11?

25:49.878 --> 25:51.245
Why won't you fight?

25:51.246 --> 25:52.713
Germany thinks it can
fix the world economy

25:52.714 --> 25:53.814
without America's help?

25:53.815 --> 25:55.849
Fine. Maybe they can.

25:55.850 --> 25:58.319
Can you just... sit down and talk to me?

25:58.320 --> 26:02.089
I came here to give the world a visual

26:02.090 --> 26:04.792
of the United States
solving the debt crisis.

26:04.793 --> 26:07.695
Instead, I'm shut out
of the entire discussion,

26:07.696 --> 26:11.332
and I'm expected to apologize
for creating a catastrophe!

26:11.333 --> 26:12.800
It's just a setback.

26:12.801 --> 26:13.901
We can still fix this.

26:13.902 --> 26:15.502
And you can still have that moment.

26:15.503 --> 26:17.236
I don't believe you.

26:20.708 --> 26:23.043
(slurring): ♪ Rather
laugh with the sinners ♪

26:23.044 --> 26:24.545
♪ Than cry with the saints ♪

26:24.546 --> 26:27.348
♪ The sinners are much more fun ♪

26:27.349 --> 26:31.151
♪ 'Cause only the good die young... ♪

26:31.152 --> 26:32.186
(laughter)

26:32.187 --> 26:33.120
You sound great!

26:33.121 --> 26:34.822
That sounds great, even in German!

26:34.823 --> 26:36.490
Wait, wait, wait, where's a bathroom?

26:36.491 --> 26:38.025
No, I need a bathroom. Uh, uh...

26:38.026 --> 26:39.693
(speaking German)

26:39.694 --> 26:41.261
(laughter)

26:41.262 --> 26:43.263
(all shouting,
laughing drunkenly)

26:43.264 --> 26:45.466
(group clamoring)

26:45.467 --> 26:48.068
Hi!

26:48.069 --> 26:49.336
(shouting in German)

26:49.337 --> 26:51.372
Yeah. I have no clue what you're saying.

26:51.373 --> 26:52.339
All right.

26:52.340 --> 26:54.440
Oh, my God.

26:55.776 --> 26:57.977
(knocks) Hello? Please hurry.

26:59.680 --> 27:00.980
No!

27:02.016 --> 27:03.851
Oh... no wonder you guys have

27:03.852 --> 27:05.519
such a good welfare system.

27:05.520 --> 27:07.421
All right.

27:07.422 --> 27:10.858
Oh...

27:10.859 --> 27:13.527
Really? You're gonna be picky
about which coins work?

27:13.528 --> 27:15.262
Oh!

27:15.263 --> 27:16.829
Damn.

27:22.369 --> 27:24.071
All right, all right.

27:24.072 --> 27:25.372
All right.

27:25.373 --> 27:28.575
Can't put a price on this.

27:28.576 --> 27:30.376
(sighs)

27:34.515 --> 27:36.749
(siren wailing)

27:49.295 --> 27:51.302
Germany is holding firm,
so we are stalled

27:51.303 --> 27:52.536
on a revised debt deal.

27:52.537 --> 27:54.491
Then we need Greece
back at the bargaining table.

27:54.492 --> 27:55.564
Which means Quinn has to

27:55.565 --> 27:57.396
- return those statues.
- Exactly.

28:00.834 --> 28:02.235
I mean, this is that moment

28:02.236 --> 28:05.031
when you guys jump in with
your awesome new ideas

28:05.032 --> 28:06.234
on how we're gonna achieve that.

28:06.235 --> 28:07.874
Ma'am, we <i>really</i> dug around.

28:07.875 --> 28:11.077
I called a friend at Treasury,
hoping for a skeleton or two.

28:11.078 --> 28:13.747
Nobody likes Quinn, but there's
nothing illegal about that.

28:13.748 --> 28:14.881
I checked with the IRS.

28:14.882 --> 28:16.883
A forensic accountant
might find something,

28:16.884 --> 28:18.251
but that'll take weeks.

28:18.252 --> 28:19.920
Greece has a major payment due tomorrow.

28:19.921 --> 28:22.355
We need something... some solution now.

28:22.356 --> 28:23.790
JAY: The big banks can cover their losses

28:23.791 --> 28:25.625
for two, maybe three days tops,

28:25.626 --> 28:30.263
but after that, we're looking at
a very bad game of dominoes.

28:30.264 --> 28:31.531
Portugal defaults.

28:31.532 --> 28:32.632
Then Spain.

28:32.633 --> 28:35.468
The Euro collapses,
exports grind to a halt,

28:35.469 --> 28:38.772
and then... your basic
global depression.

28:38.773 --> 28:41.408
All for a trio of disappointing statues.

28:41.409 --> 28:42.874
I'd hardly call them disappointing.

28:42.875 --> 28:43.510
Trust me.

28:43.511 --> 28:44.778
My girlfriend and I had to book

28:44.779 --> 28:46.313
a year in advance just to see them.

28:46.314 --> 28:47.314
Aesthetically?

28:47.315 --> 28:48.248
Not much.

28:48.249 --> 28:49.482
- A year in advance?
- Yeah.

28:49.483 --> 28:50.984
And it was elbow-to-elbow
once we got there.

28:50.985 --> 28:52.585
That's a lot of people.

28:52.586 --> 28:56.423
And I would imagine that
the division of profits

28:56.424 --> 28:59.359
would probably be pre-negotiated
by the lending nation.

28:59.360 --> 29:00.794
Like a mid-level rock band.

29:00.795 --> 29:02.762
They only make money
when they're on the road.

29:02.763 --> 29:04.898
(grunts softly)

29:04.899 --> 29:06.299
(phone vibrating)

29:06.300 --> 29:07.600
Blake!

29:07.601 --> 29:09.235
Blake's indisposed at the moment.

29:09.236 --> 29:10.637
"Indisposed" mean he's in the bathroom?

29:10.638 --> 29:13.472
Not really, but that
would've been a good idea.

29:14.641 --> 29:17.110
Hey, Stevie.

29:17.111 --> 29:19.212
Hi. How are things in Brussels?

29:19.213 --> 29:21.815
Well, they're coming along.

29:21.816 --> 29:22.916
Everything good there?

29:22.917 --> 29:23.917
Yeah. Totally.

29:23.918 --> 29:26.019
Totally not convinced.

29:26.020 --> 29:30.056
Okay, I know that President
Dalton is there. Um...

29:30.057 --> 29:31.624
I was just wondering

29:31.625 --> 29:33.026
how he seems to you.

29:33.027 --> 29:35.095
Uh, he seems stressed.

29:35.096 --> 29:36.262
Which is appropriate.

29:36.263 --> 29:37.430
Because of the debt crisis?

29:37.431 --> 29:39.532
Of course. Why?

29:39.533 --> 29:43.203
(sighs) It's just that I saw
Harrison the other day.

29:43.204 --> 29:45.839
He called me out of the blue
and wanted to have lunch,

29:45.840 --> 29:47.841
and we hung out, and it was fun,

29:47.842 --> 29:50.076
and then, you know, we
agreed to keep hanging out,

29:50.077 --> 29:52.045
but he hasn't been answering
my texts since then.

29:52.046 --> 29:53.513
Isn't he always like that?

29:53.514 --> 29:54.647
Yeah, but...

29:54.648 --> 29:56.483
I think he's kind of in trouble again.

29:56.484 --> 29:57.550
Really?

29:57.551 --> 29:59.252
Yeah, and then I saw
this thing on the news

29:59.253 --> 30:02.255
about an ambulance going
to the White House, and...

30:02.256 --> 30:03.456
I was worried.

30:03.457 --> 30:05.759
I was just wondering if Mr. Dalton

30:05.760 --> 30:07.260
has said anything to you.

30:07.261 --> 30:09.529
Um, no, he hasn't.

30:09.530 --> 30:10.764
Okay, well...

30:10.765 --> 30:13.165
I'm sure I'm just worrying for nothing.

30:15.368 --> 30:16.770
Mom?

30:16.771 --> 30:17.737
Yeah, I'm here.

30:17.738 --> 30:19.906
How are you?

30:19.907 --> 30:22.142
I mean... with everything else.

30:22.143 --> 30:24.477
Tell your father I'm fine.

30:24.478 --> 30:25.612
Hey, I really do care, too.

30:25.613 --> 30:27.781
And I really am fine.

30:27.782 --> 30:28.882
Listen, I'm glad

30:28.883 --> 30:30.717
that you're friends with Harrison again.

30:30.718 --> 30:32.851
If I am.

30:37.390 --> 30:39.492
I can smell you from here.

30:39.493 --> 30:41.127
Yeah.

30:41.128 --> 30:42.128
Imagine how I feel.

30:42.129 --> 30:43.463
What were you thinking?

30:43.464 --> 30:46.166
You are the last person I
would've expected this from.

30:46.167 --> 30:48.268
I'm sorry. My coins were too big.

30:48.269 --> 30:50.370
What is that, some sort of euphemism?

30:50.371 --> 30:52.605
No. They were pay toilets.

30:52.606 --> 30:54.074
Who has pay toilets anymore?

30:54.075 --> 30:56.476
Stop. Stop. Enough excuses.

30:56.477 --> 30:58.111
As far as I'm concerned,

30:58.112 --> 31:01.181
you are an embarrassment to
the entire State Department.

31:01.182 --> 31:04.317
We will speak again
after you have bathed.

31:04.318 --> 31:06.718
And burned your clothing.

31:10.924 --> 31:12.759
You're really leaving?

31:12.760 --> 31:15.061
What can I do for you, Elizabeth?

31:15.062 --> 31:17.263
Um...

31:17.264 --> 31:19.531
Could I get a minute, sir?

31:22.268 --> 31:24.069
Excuse us, gentlemen.

31:28.108 --> 31:30.443
I don't know why I didn't see it sooner.

31:30.444 --> 31:32.078
I've known you a long time.

31:32.079 --> 31:34.781
Only one thing gets you
this out of sorts.

31:34.782 --> 31:36.381
It's Harrison, isn't it?

31:38.051 --> 31:40.587
I wanted him to have
some time to recover

31:40.588 --> 31:42.021
before it's out in the press.

31:42.022 --> 31:43.523
It's not out.

31:43.524 --> 31:44.891
Stevie called me.

31:44.892 --> 31:46.126
They've been talking.

31:46.127 --> 31:47.793
Huh.

31:49.496 --> 31:51.798
Four days out of rehab.

31:51.799 --> 31:53.833
Lydia found him passed out in his room.

31:53.834 --> 31:56.269
Heroin. Again.

31:56.270 --> 31:58.238
Not an overdose, just a scare.

31:58.239 --> 32:00.140
But it's back to square one.

32:00.141 --> 32:02.975
Matter of time before
it's all over the news.

32:04.677 --> 32:07.113
Oh, poor kid.

32:07.114 --> 32:09.215
He didn't ask for this life.

32:09.216 --> 32:12.218
My heart goes out to him.

32:12.219 --> 32:14.820
And to you, Conrad.

32:16.589 --> 32:17.857
But Harrison's an adult now.

32:17.858 --> 32:21.628
He's in the care of people
who know how to treat him.

32:21.629 --> 32:23.963
Let them do their jobs.

32:23.964 --> 32:26.132
Let him do his.

32:26.133 --> 32:29.401
And now you do yours.

32:31.938 --> 32:34.941
September 12, you came into the office,

32:34.942 --> 32:36.943
gathered everybody around, and told us

32:36.944 --> 32:39.212
that you understood
what we were feeling.

32:39.213 --> 32:41.181
Frightened, helpless.

32:41.182 --> 32:43.850
Guilty, sad.

32:43.851 --> 32:46.052
But you told us that we had to be strong

32:46.053 --> 32:47.187
for those people who couldn't be.

32:47.188 --> 32:48.321
And then you said that

32:48.322 --> 32:49.989
anybody who wasn't up
to that could leave,

32:49.990 --> 32:51.724
no questions asked, no shame.

32:51.725 --> 32:53.226
Do you remember who left?

32:53.227 --> 32:54.561
(chuckles softly)

32:54.562 --> 32:55.962
No one.

32:55.963 --> 32:57.362
Because of you.

32:59.666 --> 33:01.668
That was a long time ago, Bess.

33:01.669 --> 33:03.369
Conrad!

33:03.370 --> 33:06.339
We can fix this.

33:06.340 --> 33:08.607
We have to at least try.

33:17.536 --> 33:19.071
Hi, Russell. Is everything okay?

33:19.072 --> 33:20.173
As far as I know.

33:20.174 --> 33:22.575
That's not what I'm here about.

33:22.576 --> 33:24.877
Come on in.

33:24.878 --> 33:26.913
That, uh...

33:26.914 --> 33:30.049
job offer from the War College, Henry...

33:30.050 --> 33:31.517
it really wasn't a question.

33:31.518 --> 33:33.019
It came from your office.

33:33.020 --> 33:35.788
From me, to be exact.

33:35.789 --> 33:38.925
You're a top religious scholar
with a military background

33:38.926 --> 33:41.460
who happens to have the
highest security clearance.

33:41.461 --> 33:42.895
It's tailor-made for you.

33:42.896 --> 33:44.063
So what are you waiting for?

33:44.064 --> 33:45.531
I like the job that I have.

33:45.532 --> 33:48.534
(scoffs) You could be
teaching your ethics class

33:48.535 --> 33:50.835
to a group of future military leaders.

33:52.038 --> 33:55.041
NSA work you did... you were good at it.

33:55.042 --> 33:58.010
You can't tell me you don't miss it.

33:58.011 --> 34:01.546
Is the teaching position a
cover for intelligence work?

34:02.315 --> 34:05.618
It would be a real job,

34:05.619 --> 34:09.789
but I can't say what may or
may not come up around it.

34:09.790 --> 34:12.992
I can say it would be public service.

34:12.993 --> 34:14.927
Isn't that the life
you're living already?

34:14.928 --> 34:17.029
Well, I'm not gonna answer
to the Defense Department.

34:17.030 --> 34:19.197
If you know my work,
you know that I've been

34:19.199 --> 34:20.967
an outspoken critic of
many of their policies.

34:20.967 --> 34:22.501
All the more reason to be there.

34:22.502 --> 34:25.137
Add a voice of reason.

34:25.138 --> 34:27.139
Help the policy makers understand

34:27.139 --> 34:30.942
Augustine's principles of just war.

34:32.311 --> 34:33.911
I'll think about it.

34:36.248 --> 34:37.750
Elizabeth will be fine with it.

34:37.751 --> 34:39.418
(chuckles)

34:39.418 --> 34:41.020
Tell me something, Russell.

34:41.021 --> 34:44.621
Does this menacing midnight
ride thing actually work?

34:50.196 --> 34:52.330
On most people.

34:55.568 --> 34:57.470
ELIZABETH: Max, your
statues are gonna go

34:57.471 --> 34:58.804
back on the road.

34:58.805 --> 35:00.907
Like a mid-level rock band.

35:00.908 --> 35:02.575
It's the only way they make money.

35:02.576 --> 35:03.876
(scoffs) What?

35:03.877 --> 35:06.178
Those guys make a fortune
in corporate sponsorship.

35:06.179 --> 35:07.847
They got clothing lines and perfumes.

35:07.848 --> 35:10.650
Well, that was someone else's analogy.

35:10.651 --> 35:12.251
But the economics are the same.

35:12.252 --> 35:13.986
You'll return the Spartan figures

35:13.987 --> 35:15.388
to the Smithsonian tomorrow,

35:15.389 --> 35:17.990
where they will begin a new
exhibition and world tour.

35:17.991 --> 35:19.892
From the Greeks' perspective,
they're still on loan.

35:19.893 --> 35:23.696
But you will get all the profits
until that debt is paid in full.

35:23.697 --> 35:25.631
But that'll take a century.

35:25.632 --> 35:27.466
And a half. But what do you care?

35:27.467 --> 35:29.435
You're all about the principle.

35:29.436 --> 35:31.871
Action is taken, confidence is restored.

35:31.872 --> 35:34.774
The economy runs on
confidence, I'm told.

35:34.775 --> 35:36.142
And money.

35:36.143 --> 35:39.478
This is a fix the Greeks can live with.

35:39.479 --> 35:41.681
And I've got to think
that your shareholders

35:41.682 --> 35:44.216
would prefer it to being hostage takers?

35:44.217 --> 35:45.785
They'll grumble,

35:45.786 --> 35:48.287
but they were getting a little
antsy about global depression.

35:48.288 --> 35:50.523
Then we have a deal?

35:50.524 --> 35:52.891
A bad one, but yes.

35:54.293 --> 35:55.261
Thank you.

35:55.262 --> 35:56.896
We'll, uh... speak soon.

35:56.897 --> 36:00.800
Ooh! (grunts) I love it when
we avoid financial Armageddon.

36:00.801 --> 36:03.836
Yeah, I don't want to
bring down the mood.

36:03.837 --> 36:05.137
One small problem.

36:05.138 --> 36:08.474
I can't reach any of the
European leaders or their staff.

36:08.475 --> 36:11.010
For all we know, they
may have gone home.

36:11.011 --> 36:12.745
Madam Secretary.

36:12.746 --> 36:13.779
Blake.

36:13.780 --> 36:15.581
Talk to me.

36:15.582 --> 36:17.316
It seems the Germans are
having a secret meeting

36:17.317 --> 36:19.018
with the other European heads of state,

36:19.019 --> 36:22.720
leaving the Americans <i>sie</i>
<i>frieren sich dich schwaenze ab.</i>

36:23.789 --> 36:25.891
I can also say, "Another
round of Schnapps."

36:25.892 --> 36:27.159
Blake was on a fact-finding mission

36:27.160 --> 36:28.828
for me last night.

36:28.829 --> 36:31.263
Although the public
urination was his idea.

36:31.264 --> 36:33.065
Nature calls the same in any language.

36:33.066 --> 36:34.767
Wait, so you were talking
to her the whole time?

36:34.768 --> 36:36.635
Except for the part
where I was in a lockup

36:36.636 --> 36:38.270
with a skinhead and a mime.

36:38.271 --> 36:40.973
Ma'am, these tradecraft
episodes would work even better

36:40.974 --> 36:43.242
if you would fill us all in.

36:43.243 --> 36:45.311
Well, that's actually the
opposite of how they work.

36:45.312 --> 36:46.946
When is this meeting?

36:46.947 --> 36:48.647
(phone chimes)

36:48.648 --> 36:50.582
Funny you should ask. Right now.

36:54.186 --> 36:56.789
Mr. President, Germany
is cutting us out.

36:56.790 --> 36:58.758
They're having a secret
meeting to kill the deal.

36:58.759 --> 37:00.092
Where?

37:00.093 --> 37:02.894
Right here, third floor, Petite Ballroom.

37:03.629 --> 37:05.097
Change of plan.

37:05.098 --> 37:07.699
The secretary and I have
a meeting to crash.

37:15.341 --> 37:17.343
Move away from the door.

37:17.344 --> 37:18.810
Now.

37:21.213 --> 37:22.914
Should we knock?

37:25.151 --> 37:26.852
Excuse me, Mr. President!

37:26.853 --> 37:28.687
Sorry we're late.

37:28.688 --> 37:30.322
Sir,

37:30.323 --> 37:34.360
you and your secretary of state
are not part of this meeting.

37:34.361 --> 37:36.094
We are now.

37:36.829 --> 37:39.865
What I mean is you're not welcome.

37:39.866 --> 37:41.367
Oh, we'll get over it.

37:41.368 --> 37:44.036
Our minds are firmly made up.

37:44.037 --> 37:45.738
No more deals.

37:45.739 --> 37:48.741
The Greeks must be punished
for their recent behavior.

37:48.742 --> 37:51.510
We are considering kicking
them out of the eurozone.

37:51.511 --> 37:52.978
This is not the moment to retreat.

37:52.979 --> 37:55.648
Mr. President, we are
not going to sit here

37:55.649 --> 37:57.917
and listen to you argue
for your own interests.

37:57.918 --> 38:00.553
After recent events,

38:00.554 --> 38:03.989
you don't have enough authority
to hold anyone's attention.

38:03.990 --> 38:07.760
I'm glad you brought that
up, Chancellor Schulz.

38:07.761 --> 38:09.995
Your attention.

38:09.996 --> 38:13.365
Or, uh, your attention
spans, more specifically.

38:13.366 --> 38:16.068
Are your memories really that short?

38:16.069 --> 38:18.737
I look around this room, and
I don't see a single nation,

38:18.738 --> 38:20.873
large or small,

38:20.874 --> 38:22.241
that is immune to misfortune.

38:22.242 --> 38:23.876
Ireland.

38:23.877 --> 38:25.077
Three years ago,

38:25.078 --> 38:28.447
your bonds were junk and
needed a bailout to survive.

38:28.448 --> 38:30.015
Spain.

38:30.016 --> 38:32.985
Your unemployment rate is at 26%.

38:32.986 --> 38:35.554
An entire generation is leaving home.

38:35.555 --> 38:36.889
Portugal.

38:36.890 --> 38:38.858
Yesterday,

38:38.859 --> 38:41.460
your debt was 129% of GDP.

38:41.461 --> 38:44.463
Do you really want to face
the music by yourself?

38:44.464 --> 38:46.531
Chancellor, you're shaking your head.

38:47.366 --> 38:49.034
But this is not a morality play.

38:49.035 --> 38:52.003
The very future of your
citizens is at stake.

38:52.738 --> 38:55.040
We can stand together,

38:55.041 --> 38:58.611
as we did at the end of
the Second World War,

38:58.612 --> 39:00.878
or we can wither alone.

39:02.281 --> 39:05.584
Now, anyone who wants to leave,

39:05.585 --> 39:07.585
there's the door.

39:08.487 --> 39:11.556
(quiet murmuring)

39:12.591 --> 39:14.160
Good.

39:14.161 --> 39:17.395
I think it's time we all
got down to business.

39:25.137 --> 39:27.106
Hi.

39:27.107 --> 39:28.674
Hi.

39:28.675 --> 39:30.009
(chuckles)

39:30.010 --> 39:31.810
How you doing?

39:31.811 --> 39:33.812
Uh, you're looking at it.

39:33.813 --> 39:35.481
Sorry I didn't call.

39:35.482 --> 39:37.016
I'm kind of a lousy friend.

39:37.017 --> 39:38.284
Stop. It's fine.

39:38.285 --> 39:39.585
No, it's not.

39:39.586 --> 39:40.819
I'm...

39:40.820 --> 39:43.122
I wish I could tell you that
I was gonna get better,

39:43.123 --> 39:44.790
but I don't... I don't know.

39:44.791 --> 39:47.860
I'm probably gonna be a
mess for a little while.

39:47.861 --> 39:50.496
Hopefully a sober one.

39:50.497 --> 39:52.464
But, uh, I don't know.

39:52.465 --> 39:54.466
It's the pressure to act
like a normal person,

39:54.467 --> 39:57.469
it makes me feel, like, caged in,

39:57.470 --> 40:00.905
so I-I'm, um... not gonna do that.

40:02.641 --> 40:04.609
Look, Harry.

40:06.245 --> 40:08.314
I'm the secretary of state's daughter,

40:08.315 --> 40:10.683
and I flamed out of college,

40:10.684 --> 40:12.952
I maxed out all of my
mother's credit cards,

40:12.953 --> 40:16.889
and then I had to move
back in with my parents.

40:16.890 --> 40:19.525
I think we can find some common ground.

40:19.526 --> 40:22.228
I still win.

40:22.229 --> 40:23.996
You were always so competitive.

40:23.997 --> 40:26.564
(both laugh)

40:27.333 --> 40:28.968
Oh, hey.

40:28.969 --> 40:30.736
Sorry, I didn't hear the trumpets.

40:30.737 --> 40:32.238
I got rid of those.

40:32.239 --> 40:33.239
Too distracting.

40:33.240 --> 40:34.340
Hi, Mr. Dalton.

40:34.341 --> 40:35.975
Hi, Stevie.

40:35.976 --> 40:37.309
- Good to see you.
- You, too.

40:37.310 --> 40:38.711
Heard things went well in Brussels,

40:38.712 --> 40:40.379
so you're back on top.

40:40.380 --> 40:42.948
For the moment.

40:42.949 --> 40:45.083
Um, well, I should get going.

40:45.818 --> 40:48.820
I'll call you.

40:58.063 --> 41:00.065
The house looks amazing.

41:00.066 --> 41:02.034
Now everything's working.

41:02.035 --> 41:04.503
How'd you get water pressure
up to the second floor?

41:04.504 --> 41:06.171
Mad skills.

41:06.172 --> 41:07.506
Called a plumber.

41:07.507 --> 41:09.141
(both laugh)

41:09.142 --> 41:11.176
You know, I've been thinking...

41:11.177 --> 41:12.878
You're gonna take the War College job.

41:12.879 --> 41:14.213
I knew it, I knew it.

41:14.214 --> 41:15.514
I mean, you got to.

41:15.515 --> 41:18.183
You know, it's challenging, it has scope.

41:18.184 --> 41:20.252
It's a chance for you to
influence policy makers.

41:20.253 --> 41:22.254
How do you turn that down?

41:22.255 --> 41:24.923
I know that you liked
your work at the NSA

41:24.924 --> 41:26.925
and you kind of miss a life of service.

41:26.926 --> 41:29.261
And if I'm gonna be in it,
why shouldn't you be?

41:29.262 --> 41:32.264
You know, we always talked
about being all in.

41:32.265 --> 41:33.932
And this is it, this is our chance.

41:33.933 --> 41:36.368
We're gonna let this
place go and go for it.

41:36.369 --> 41:38.037
I was gonna say that I think

41:38.038 --> 41:40.406
it would look really
nice with red shutters.

41:40.407 --> 41:42.441
Oh.

41:42.442 --> 41:43.942
Really?

41:43.943 --> 41:47.279
I was gonna say all that
other stuff after dinner.

41:47.280 --> 41:48.814
- I nailed it?
- Yeah, pretty much.

41:48.815 --> 41:51.050
I mean, it makes no sense
for us to keep this farm,

41:51.051 --> 41:52.851
especially if I'm gonna
take that other job.

41:52.852 --> 41:55.220
It's a much bigger commitment,
I'll be traveling a lot.

41:55.221 --> 41:57.523
I just wanted to be sure
that you were okay before...

41:57.524 --> 41:59.124
Okay.

41:59.125 --> 42:00.526
Uh, you don't have to say that.

42:00.527 --> 42:01.827
We can still think about it.

42:01.828 --> 42:03.495
I'm saying it... I don't
want to think about it.

42:03.496 --> 42:04.797
I'm tired of thinking about it.

42:04.798 --> 42:05.964
You know what?

42:05.965 --> 42:09.868
We can do all this bucolic
stuff when we're old.

42:09.869 --> 42:12.271
We're not old? That's awesome.

42:12.272 --> 42:14.573
This gets better and better.

42:14.574 --> 42:16.008
We got to tell the kids.

42:16.009 --> 42:17.242
Yeah, you do.

42:17.243 --> 42:18.677
- I...?
- That's gonna be rough.

42:18.678 --> 42:20.312
They love it here.

42:20.313 --> 42:22.781
(sighs) We're not ruining
their lives, are we?

42:22.782 --> 42:24.450
(chuckles) If we haven't
ruined their lives already,

42:24.451 --> 42:25.951
believe me, this isn't gonna do it.

42:25.952 --> 42:28.620
Okay, but if anybody starts crying,

42:28.621 --> 42:30.422
can I say that it was your idea?

42:30.423 --> 42:31.790
- My...? Okay, sure.
- ALISON: Hey, guys.

42:31.791 --> 42:32.958
I drew the short straw,

42:32.959 --> 42:34.893
so I get to tell you that
we're all really bored

42:34.894 --> 42:36.495
and wondering if we could
cut this weekend short

42:36.496 --> 42:38.529
and head home.

42:39.264 --> 42:42.706
Okay, it can be my idea. (chuckles)

